Enhancement: Add `--include-from-raw` option to the `restore` command

The `restore` command's `--include` and `--include-file` options matched
each entry as a `filepath.Match` glob, which gives some characters a
special meaning (`*`, `?`, `[`, `]`, `\`). For paths whose names contain
brackets in particular, there was no portable way to request a single
file: Go's `filepath.Match` rejects the POSIX class self-escape `[[]`
and on Windows the backslash escape is unavailable because `\` is a
path separator. The only workaround was to broaden the pattern with a
wildcard like `Q3 *.pdf`, which over-restores every sibling matching
the relaxed pattern — wasted bandwidth and disk for callers that
already had exact paths.

The `restore` command now accepts `--include-from-raw FILE`, mirroring
the existing `backup --files-from-raw`: the file contains
NUL-terminated absolute paths, each one matched literally against the
snapshot tree. Glob metacharacters lose their special meaning in this
mode, so paths containing brackets, asterisks, or question marks
round-trip cleanly. The flag composes with `--include`, `--iinclude`,
and `--include-file` (any matching pattern selects the file). The same
flag is registered on the `rewrite` command, which shares the include
infrastructure.

